{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17625398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17625398"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:24:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:24:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17021"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17021"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.84,0.05,0,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9711"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70410"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9711"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17021"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55874"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5392"},{"type":"tags","id":"5438"},{"type":"tags","id":"5439"},{"type":"tags","id":"5528"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22853"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22857"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70410"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EInfectious disease transmission within populations can be prevented when a critical proportion of individuals are immune to the pathogen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the concept of herd immunity?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Protection of individuals through personal immunity only","Prevention of disease spread through population-level immunity","Complete elimination of a pathogen from the environment","Natural selection of resistant individuals over time","Direct protection of unvaccinated people by vaccinated people"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHerd immunity refers to \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevention of disease spread through population-level immunity\u003C/strong\u003E. This phenomenon emerges when sufficient numbers of people in a population possess immunity, making it difficult for pathogens to locate susceptible hosts and maintain transmission chains. The effect protects the entire population by reducing overall disease transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtection of individuals through personal immunity only\u003C/strong\u003E focuses solely on individual protection without considering the broader population effects essential to herd immunity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete elimination of a pathogen from the environment\u003C/strong\u003E exceeds what is needed for herd immunity, which only requires enough population immunity to interrupt transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENatural selection of resistant individuals over time\u003C/strong\u003E describes evolutionary adaptation rather than the acquired immunity that underlies herd immunity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect protection of unvaccinated people by vaccinated people\u003C/strong\u003E incorrectly suggests direct rather than population-level protection through reduced transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe number of immune individuals needed for herd immunity differs depending on the pathogen. Highly infectious diseases like measles require approximately 95% immunity, while less infectious diseases like influenza may need 50-80%.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Herd immunity occurs when a proportion of the population is immune to prevent sustained disease transmission.","The herd immunity threshold varies by disease based on the pathogen\u0027s basic reproduction number (R0).","Immunity can be achieved through vaccination or natural infection, with vaccination being the safer approach."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55874"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17021"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55874"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T22:47:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T22:47:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9711"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70410"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},